    id: 'lighthouse-keepers-daughter',
    title: 'The Lighthouse Keeper\'s Daughter',
    genre: 'Folklore / Legend',
    kidSafeText: `In a small village by the sea, there lived a lighthouse keeper named Thomas and his daughter, Eleanor. They lived in a tall lighthouse that helped ships find their way safely through the fog and rocks.

Eleanor had lived in the lighthouse her whole life. Her father had raised her there after her mother passed away when Eleanor was born. Thomas taught Eleanor everything—how to read, how to understand the sea, and how to keep the lighthouse burning bright.

One autumn, something strange happened. A ship ran into the rocks even though the lighthouse was shining brightly. When Thomas went to check, the ship was empty—no people, no crew, just cargo. Among the cargo, he found a beautiful music box.

When Thomas opened the music box, it played a haunting melody. Eleanor heard it from the tower above and began to cry, though she didn't know why. That night, Eleanor became very sick. She lay in bed, speaking to people no one else could see.

"The sea is calling me," Eleanor whispered. "I've always belonged there."

Thomas sat beside his daughter, worried and confused. He began looking through his wife's old belongings, things he hadn't touched in fifteen years. He found his wife's journal.

In the journal, his wife had written about her past. She had washed ashore years before, drawn to the lighthouse. She wrote about loving Thomas but feeling a pull toward the sea. "When our child is born," she had written, "I hope she will be free to choose her own path."

Thomas understood then. He went to Eleanor and held her hand. "I know you feel called to the sea," he said gently. "And I won't keep you from where you belong."

Eleanor's fever broke at dawn. She rose from her bed, and something had changed—she seemed to glow with a soft, ocean light. She hugged her father one last time.

"I will keep ships safe," she promised. "Not from the tower, but from the waters below. No more ships will wreck here."

She walked down to the shore as the sun rose, and the sea rose up to meet her like an old friend. Thomas continued tending the lighthouse for many years after. And it was true—no ships ever wrecked on those rocks again.

Fishermen would sometimes see a glowing figure in the water, and they knew it was Eleanor, keeping her promise, a guardian between the land and the sea.`,
