    id: 'last-laugh',
    title: 'The Last Laugh',
    genre: 'Humor',
    kidSafeText: `Marcus had been a comedian for thirty years, but he had a problem—nobody ever laughed at his jokes. Not once! He practiced his timing, memorized his jokes, and performed with confidence. But every time he finished, the audience would sit in polite silence.

Despite this, Marcus kept performing. Club owners kept booking him because people were curious. They wanted to see what would happen when he got on stage. Marcus was famous, but not in the way he wanted to be.

One night, Marcus decided to try something completely different. Instead of telling his practiced jokes, he decided to tell the truth.

"I'm the worst comedian alive," he began. "I've spent thirty years making audiences wish they'd stayed home."

The audience laughed! Not politely—genuinely, deeply. They laughed at his honesty and his willingness to admit the truth.

"For years, I thought comedy was about the perfect joke," Marcus continued. "But apparently, comedy is about admitting you're a disaster and watching other people realize they're not alone in being disasters."

More laughter filled the room. Marcus felt something shift inside him. He realized he'd been trying to be clever when he should have been trying to be honest.

For the rest of that night, Marcus talked about his real life—his failures, his silly mistakes, the time he accidentally joined a dance class thinking it was a cooking class. Each story made people laugh harder.

When he left the stage, people actually applauded! The club owner booked him for more shows. A talent agent asked to represent him.

The beautiful thing, Marcus thought, was that he'd finally become successful at comedy by completely changing what he thought comedy was. He'd spent thirty years trying to make people laugh with perfect jokes. But he only succeeded when he stopped trying to be perfect and started being real.

Years later, when other comedians asked Marcus for advice, he would say: "The secret to making people laugh is to stop trying to be funny and start trying to be honest. The rest takes care of itself."

And that's how Marcus learned that sometimes the best way to succeed is to stop pretending and just be yourself.`,
