    id: 'signal-from-kepler',
    title: 'The Signal From Kepler-442b',
    genre: 'Science Fiction',
    kidSafeText: `Dr. Amara had been listening to space for twenty-two years when she finally heard something amazing. A signal came from a planet called Kepler-442b, very far away. The signal was too organized to be random—it was a message from another civilization!

The world changed overnight. Governments held emergency meetings. Scientists worked together to understand the message. Dr. Amara found herself at the center of the biggest discovery in human history.

But there was something concerning in the message. The civilization on Kepler-442b had met three other intelligent species before. Two of those species were no longer around. The signal included information about what happened: both species had disappeared about 850 years after first contact.

"They're trying to warn us," said Dr. James, Amara's colleague. "They're telling us what happened to the others so we can be prepared."

But prepared for what? That was the big question. The signal didn't mention any danger or threat. It just showed the timeline—first contact, then a long period, then silence.

Dr. Amara worked with scientists from around the world to understand what had happened. They developed a theory: maybe the problem wasn't an outside threat. Maybe learning that we're not alone in the universe was itself the challenge. Some civilizations might have struggled with that knowledge.

"We're not being warned about an invasion," Amara explained to world leaders. "We're being warned that knowing we're not alone might change how we see ourselves. We need to be ready for that change."

The room was quiet as everyone thought about this. Then a delegate asked, "So what do we do? Pretend we didn't hear the message?"

Amara had thought about this for months. "We respond," she said. "But not with facts or power. We respond with what makes us special. We tell them about our art, our music, our stories. We tell them about the things we create because we need to express ourselves, not just survive."

It took weeks to create humanity's response. Billions of people contributed—songs, stories, images, all encoded into a signal aimed at Kepler-442b. When it was sent, there was a feeling of peace. Humanity had chosen to share who they really were.

The response would take 430 years to reach Kepler-442b, and another 430 years for their reply to come back. But that was okay. Humanity had learned something important: we're not just a species that survives. We're a species that creates, that loves, that dreams. And we would face whatever came next knowing that about ourselves.`,
