    title: 'The Clockmaker\'s Secret',
    genre: 'Fantasy',
    kidSafeText: `In a city where time flowed normally, there was a shop with a sign: "All Clocks Repaired, All Hours Mended." The clockmaker was an old woman named Irina, and her specialty was fixing broken time.

People came to her with clocks that wouldn't keep time, watches that ran backwards, hourglasses that had gotten stuck. But Irina's real specialty was more unusual. She fixed temporal problems—moments that had gotten stuck, people living the same day repeatedly, hours that had somehow been lost.

A young man came to her one day, explaining that he'd lost six months. Not forgotten them—he'd actually lost them. He'd been experiencing time normally until one Tuesday, when he'd suddenly jumped from March to September. Six months simply gone. He was desperate to understand what had happened.

Irina examined him carefully, as if he were one of her clocks. She studied the way he moved through space, the rhythm of his breathing, the pattern of his thoughts. Finally, she said: "You didn't lose those months. They lost you. You made a choice that broke the flow. Time moved on without you, and when you rejoined the world, six months had passed."

"That's impossible," he said.

"Tell me about that Tuesday," she said. "About the moment the jump happened."

The young man described it: a decision point. His girlfriend had asked him to move with her to another city, leave his life behind. He'd been about to say no. And then, in that moment of indecision, something had broken. And when he came back to himself, it was September, and his girlfriend had left, and six months had passed without him.

Irina nodded. "You paused in time because you couldn't accept moving forward. Part of you stepped outside of the flow, didn't age, didn't experience. When you finally accepted that time had continued without you, you re-joined the world. But those months were gone."

"Can you give them back to me?"

Irina was quiet for a long time. "I could," she said finally. "I could repair the break. I could make it so those six months happened for you. But they already happened for everyone else. For your girlfriend, for your city, for the world. If I give you those months back, you'll experience them while everyone else has moved on. You'll be living in a different timeline."

"I don't care. I just want those months back."

Irina began to work. She took out tools that seemed impossible—delicate instruments made of crystallized moments, springs wound from hours, tiny gears that measured fractions of seconds. She worked for hours, and slowly, she began to rewind the man's timeline, pulling those lost six months back into his experience.

But as she did, something extraordinary happened. As the six months became real again, they began to change. Because time wasn't just a path forward—it was a negotiation. The young man's experience of those months was shaped by the knowledge he now had: that his girlfriend would leave, that he would lose this time. So the months he lived, as Irina rewound them into reality, became different months. He experienced them knowing what was coming. He made different choices. He reached out to his girlfriend. They had conversations he wouldn't have had. The timeline bent and reformed around his new awareness.

When it was done, the young man had not lost six months. He had gained them—six months lived with the knowledge of their importance, six months where he was consciously choosing, rather than unconsciously drifting.

"How much do I owe you?" he asked.

Irina smiled. "Nothing. Everyone who comes to me has already paid. They've already learned the real lesson: that you can't fix broken time by repairing the past. You can only fix broken time by accepting it and moving forward differently."

The young man left, and a new customer came in. And Irina returned to her work, knowing that every clock she fixed, every moment she mended, was just helping people understand that they had far more power over time than they realized. They could choose to move forward. They could choose to live consciously. That was the real secret: time didn't trap you. You could only trap yourself.`,
